WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:17.780
All right, we've been talking about all different types of components within a system.

00:17.780 --> 00:34.020
And now we're going to teach my my daughter here.

00:34.020 --> 00:37.860
All right, we've been talking about all different types of components within a system.

00:37.860 --> 00:42.180
And now we're going to teach my my daughter here about storage within a system.

00:42.180 --> 00:46.380
We're going to talk about the two primary types of storage within a system, primary storage

00:46.380 --> 00:48.300
and secondary storage.

00:48.300 --> 00:51.620
So this is where we keep the bits in our computer system.

00:51.620 --> 00:55.100
Later in life, this is where you'll keep your like Instagram photos or whatever the

00:55.100 --> 00:57.620
kids are doing that when you're growing up, okay?

00:57.620 --> 01:00.140
So what does primary storage mean?

01:00.140 --> 01:05.060
Primary storage means it's volatile memory, whereas secondary storage is often referred

01:05.060 --> 01:06.980
to as non-volatile memory.

01:06.980 --> 01:08.980
So what's that word volatile mean?

01:08.980 --> 01:13.420
Well, soon you'll learn that volatile means it's something that can sort of disappear

01:13.420 --> 01:14.420
at regular temperatures.

01:14.860 --> 01:18.380
And that's a really good way of thinking about primary storage or volatile memory.

01:18.380 --> 01:23.340
If the power gets pulled, any of that data in volatile memory disappears.

01:23.340 --> 01:24.540
It's gone.

01:24.540 --> 01:30.620
Whereas in non-volatile memory, the data remains even when the system is powered down.

01:30.620 --> 01:36.580
So let's look at some examples of both primary and secondary storage and we'll start with

01:36.580 --> 01:37.860
primary storage.

01:37.860 --> 01:42.580
So some really good examples of primary storage are things like my daughter's trying to

01:43.380 --> 01:44.940
eat my finger here, she's teething.

01:44.940 --> 01:50.020
So examples of primary storage are cash, registers, RAM.

01:50.020 --> 01:54.140
And all of these are very, very high speed forms of storage.

01:54.140 --> 01:57.180
So what do we primarily use volatile memory for?

01:57.180 --> 02:02.620
We use primary or volatile memory for data that's actively being used by the system,

02:02.620 --> 02:08.620
for programs that have been loaded that are in memory, that the CPU is currently processing.

02:08.620 --> 02:13.620
And what we want this primary storage for is for the data that needs to be accessed very,

02:13.620 --> 02:14.860
very quickly.

02:14.860 --> 02:19.980
And so cash, registers, this is actually data or this is actually storage built into

02:19.980 --> 02:21.700
the processor itself.

02:21.700 --> 02:26.580
Whereas RAM, RAM, access memory is actually memory modules built into the system.

02:26.580 --> 02:28.340
But it's quite fast.

02:28.340 --> 02:31.220
So what are the pros and cons of primary storage?

02:31.220 --> 02:37.660
Well, as we talked about, primary storage, very, very fast, but it is volatile.

02:37.740 --> 02:39.060
Like you're getting here.

02:39.060 --> 02:41.420
So what about secondary storage?

02:41.420 --> 02:43.100
It's kind of the inverse.

02:43.100 --> 02:49.300
Examples of secondary storage are things like magnetic hard drives, optical media drives,

02:49.300 --> 02:51.660
tapes, solid state drives.

02:51.660 --> 02:54.380
These are all examples of secondary storage.

02:54.380 --> 02:58.460
They're not nearly as fast, but they can store a lot more data.

02:58.460 --> 03:01.580
A lot more pictures of you, cutie.

03:01.580 --> 03:05.380
So what do we primarily use secondary storage for?

03:05.380 --> 03:10.220
We use secondary storage for storing the data and the program code when it's not being

03:10.220 --> 03:11.220
used.

03:11.220 --> 03:16.180
So pictures, things like that, data from programs, movies, they're stored in our secondary

03:16.180 --> 03:17.460
storage.

03:17.460 --> 03:22.540
Now, let's talk about one other concept and it's known as virtual memory.

03:22.540 --> 03:26.820
And to explain virtual memory, we have to understand a little bit how a computer system

03:26.820 --> 03:27.820
actually works.

03:27.820 --> 03:33.140
So you've probably noticed when you double click on an icon like Word, it actually takes

03:33.140 --> 03:35.860
a little bit of time for that program to load.

03:35.860 --> 03:39.940
And in fact, there's often what we call a load screen.

03:39.940 --> 03:41.860
So what is a load screen?

03:41.860 --> 03:46.780
A load screen is where the program is telling you it's actually taking data from secondary

03:46.780 --> 03:52.340
storage, from slower hard drives, and it's moving it into RAM, into memory, much higher

03:52.340 --> 03:53.860
speed storage.

03:53.860 --> 03:58.140
And the reason you want this to occur is that the processor works so incredibly quickly.

03:58.140 --> 04:01.060
It's always going through calculations.

04:01.060 --> 04:05.140
We've had to wait for a very long time for some data that's requested to come back from

04:05.140 --> 04:06.820
say secondary storage.

04:06.820 --> 04:10.660
It would really significantly slow the computer system down.

04:10.660 --> 04:14.580
So when we load a program, what we're actually doing is transferring data from secondary

04:14.580 --> 04:19.860
storage, the hard drive, into primary storage, RAM, random access memory.

04:19.860 --> 04:21.100
Can you say that out loud?

04:21.100 --> 04:22.540
Probably not yet.

04:22.540 --> 04:25.660
So there's a problem though with this.

04:25.660 --> 04:29.660
If you've got too many programs running, if you've loaded too many programs, you're

04:29.660 --> 04:33.620
going to run out of this primary storage known as RAM.

04:33.620 --> 04:36.100
And you've probably heard numbers relate to your computer systems.

04:36.100 --> 04:41.300
It's not uncommon that a computer will have, say, four or eight gigabytes of RAM, and

04:41.300 --> 04:43.380
you'll have like, terabytes of storage.

04:43.380 --> 04:47.780
So RAM is really, really small, relatively, to the secondary storage.

04:47.780 --> 04:52.220
And so the problem we had is if we've loaded too many programs into RAM, we start to run

04:52.220 --> 04:53.780
out of RAM.

04:53.780 --> 04:57.980
And a computer system, if it were to run out of memory entirely, the system would crash.

04:57.980 --> 05:00.220
And in fact, we used to see this a lot.

05:00.220 --> 05:02.740
So there used to be something called the blue screen of death.

05:02.740 --> 05:05.020
Hopefully, you'll never have to see that in your life.

05:05.020 --> 05:09.700
But in Windows, if you had too many things loaded and the system ran out of RAM, ran out

05:09.700 --> 05:21.420
of this primary storage, you'd actually get a blue screen, the system would crash.

05:21.420 --> 05:26.180
So a way that we found, the industry is found to actually deal with this problem is to use

05:26.180 --> 05:28.020
what is known as virtual memory.

05:28.020 --> 05:34.420
And this is the concept, drooly face, where we move some data out of RAM back to the hard

05:34.420 --> 05:35.420
drive.

05:35.420 --> 05:37.860
And we temporarily store it on the hard drive until it's neat again.

05:37.860 --> 05:42.420
And then we can move it again back from the hard drive, woo, we were falling, back into

05:42.420 --> 05:43.420
primary storage.

05:43.420 --> 05:45.500
And that's the concept of virtual memory.

05:45.500 --> 05:49.380
It's simply this idea that some data that's not being used very often is moved out of

05:49.380 --> 05:51.420
RAM onto the hard drive.

05:51.420 --> 05:54.340
And then when it's needed again, back into memory.

05:54.340 --> 05:57.620
With the overall effect, it definitely slows down the system.

05:57.620 --> 06:01.340
But the system keeps running, so that's virtual memory.

